Query 4
SELECT * FROM account
WHERE customer_id = 3;

Total Queries

1 + 3 = 4 Queries

If there are:

100 Customers

Queries become

1 + 100 = 101 Queries

This is the N+1 Problem.




Why Does It Happen?

Usually because of

@OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)

The child collection is loaded only when accessed.

When you call:

customer.getAccounts();

Hibernate fires another SQL query

Solution 1: Fetch Join (Best Solution)
.................................................
.....................................
@Query("""
       SELECT c
       FROM Customer c
       JOIN FETCH c.accounts
       """)
List<Customer> findAllCustomers();

Generated SQL

SELECT *
FROM customer c
JOIN account a
ON c.id=a.customer_id;

Only one SQL query.


Solution 2: Entity Graph
.......................................
................................................
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = "accounts")
List<Customer> findAll();

Hibernate fetches customers and accounts together.


Solution 3: Change Fetch Type (Use Carefully)
................................
@OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.EAGER)

Hibernate loads accounts immediately.

⚠️ Not recommended for large collections because it may load unnecessary data.


Solution 4: DTO Projection (Recommended for REST APIs)
.........................
Instead of returning entities:

public record CustomerDTO(
        String name,
        List<AccountDTO> accounts
) {}

Fetch only required columns.

Benefits:

Better performance
Smaller JSON response
Avoids lazy-loading issues
Avoids N+1 in many cases



